<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h3>Tutorial 6. Sewing a Mock-Up Dress after the Adjusted Pattern. Review of Materials Used. Peculiarities of Working with Taffeta. </h3>
<p></p>
<p><strong>I have sewn a mock-up dress using my adjusted patterns and my client has tried it on. </strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image002.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image004.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>There was only one inaccuracy that concerned the neckline depth at the front.</strong> I have made a marking and I'm going to make it rounder. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image006.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>The rest fit literally perfectly both from the front and back. The shoulders were in the right place, too. </strong>If you put this mock-up on the dress-form and carefully stuff all hollows, you'll have a proper imitation of your client's figure, i.e. a custom dress-form with her body dimensions. It is also really easy to measure the skirt length down from the waistline when you have a mock-up put on the dress-form.&nbsp; </p>
<p><strong>I have adjusted the central front piece (trimmed the neckline and made it rounder) and now the cutting process can finally begin.&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image008.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></strong></p>
<p><strong>But first I would like to speak about the fabrics I'm going to sew with. </strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>I have chosen elastic taffeta for the skirt because it holds its shape rather well. </strong></p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image010.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>Its elastic thread is parallel to the selvage so I will cut my garment lengthwise to make the waistline parallel to the crosswise grain and prevent it from getting stretched.&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image012.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Please be very careful when working with acetate fabrics!</strong> Even though I've purchased white taffeta, it will look much more yellow than the skirt after I duplicate it with iron-on batiste. This fabric is translucent so the iron-on material will show through. Besides taffeta stretches a lot and there's a big chance the iron-on fabric will eventually start coming off when in wear or even during a fit test.&nbsp; </p>
<p><strong>The only way out of this challenging situation is making taffeta a third layer! What do I mean by that?</strong> I am going to use stretch satin for the lining and for the base of the dress. It stretches crosswise and I will cut it crosswise, too.&nbsp; </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image014.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>This satin will serve as the base and the lining and there'll be a third taffeta layer at the top. I recommend placing the second satin layer (the base) under the taffeta matte side up.&nbsp; First I'll join those pieces and then I'll work on them as a single piece.&nbsp; </p>
<p><strong>I purposely want to show you how to work with a third layer of fabric on this dress. </strong>It's a very frequently asked question and a very common problem that's particularly relevant when sewing white dresses. Those of you experienced in sewing wedding dresses know that if you duplicate a one-piece dress down to the hip level, the border with the iron-on material will show through the translucent white fabric. In that case you have to either duplicate the fabric down to the very bottom of the garment or use a third layer, i.e. overlay it with the main fabric. First you duplicate and assemble the base of the garment and then you overlay it with the desired face fabric.&nbsp; </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image016.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>Our skirt will have taffeta base and lining with several layers of netting in-between to enhance the volume. </strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image018.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p>The netting is whiter than the taffeta so I will use some matching white lace to decorate the waistline and the bodice and balance out the shades. When you accept a similar order, never forget that white taffeta tends to be somewhat yellowish while white lace and netting can actually be snow-white. That's why if your dress model involves similar netting, you should think of some d�cor to balance out the unlike shades and warn the client in advance so it doesn't come as a surprise. Taffeta materials are highly sought-after! They hold their shape really well and are easy to sew with. It�s the reason I've chosen taffeta for our shoulder-seam garment.&nbsp; </p>
<p><strong>But let us return to the patterns. </strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image020.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<p><strong>The full skirt of our dress starts right from the waist. </strong>An inexperienced seamstress might make the wrong conclusion looking at this dress model and assume the corset top stops at the waistline and the skirt is attached at that level. This is the main and most common mistake made by beginners who are still new to corset-tailoring and not very familiar with the peculiarities of corset garments. First of all, the corset restricts the figure solely at the waistline. It holds around the waistline alone. So if there's a joining seam going along the waistline of the corset, it will bite into the skin. In this case if the skirt attached around the waistline is not full enough, your client's skin will start bulging out at the sides when you tighten the corset.&nbsp; Moreover, when your client puts this garment on for the first time and tries to sit down and then stand up, the vertical bones of the corset will bite into her stomach making her feel incredibly uncomfortable. She won't be able to enjoy the party! <strong>That's why you must never make a joining seam at the waistline of the corset in garments that look as though their top and bottom were joined along the waistline! </strong>&nbsp;Of course you shouldn't make the corset too long either. <strong>I highly recommend that the corset top should reach down to the stomach level (usually 12cm below the waistline). It is more than enough! </strong>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Besides our particular model features a short skirt and it's obvious that a hoop petticoat won't do in this case. What we need instead are many layers of netting that will keep the skirt spread out. <strong>And again, it wouldn't be reasonable to start attaching these numerous layers from the waistline. </strong>The base of the skirt and its overlay with beautifully draped folds will be attached around the waistline. And if we put layers of netting underneath the main skirt, the entire construction will be way too thick in the waist. That's why our netting petticoat will be attached to the bottom of the corset, i.e. at the stomach level. </p>
<p>If you follow my advice, the wide waistband of the corset will hold the entire dress and nothing will bite into your client's skin. She will feel confident in this dress because it won't shift around her body despite having shoulder seams. Frankly speaking, the shoulder seams of this dress perform a purely decorative function because there only intended support area is the waistline. </p>
<p><strong>I prepare the patterns for the cutting process by trimming them along the stomach line.</strong> Since the patterns are not that large, you can first duplicate a piece of fabric with iron-on batiste, then lay the patterns over it and cut them out the way you do it for a corset. </p>
<p>
<img src="https://corsetacademy.s3.amazonaws.com/wedding%20dresses/wedding%202/Tutorial%206_files/image022.jpg" class="img-responsive center-block"></p>
<h3> </h3>

